        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "A Temperature-insensitive Micromachined Resonant Accelerometer with Thermal Stress Isolation "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                78,
                68,
                919,
                133
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Yonggang Yin, Zhengxiang Fang, Jingxin Dong, Yunfeng Liu and Fengtian Han  \nState Key Laboratory of Precision Measurement Technology and Instruments, Tsinghua University, Beijing, China  \nEmail: hft@mail.tsinghua.edu.cn "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                204,
                181,
                792,
                246
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Abstract—Micromachined resonant accelerometers, especially those devices fabricated by silicon on glass technology, suffer from temperature drift caused by inherent thermal stress. This paper introduces two methods to attenuate the effect of thermal stress. The locations of the bonding anchors are first optimized in layout design to reduce the thermal stress effect along the acceleration-sensitive axis. Moreover, the glass substrate is designed as a dedicated shape to isolate the thermal stress generated during the die attach process. Experimental results on several prototype accelerometers show that the differential temperature sensitivity is reduced to  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "10.5\\mu \\mathrm{g} / ^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " and the 1-hour bias stability reaches  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.7\\mu \\mathrm{g}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                66,
                272,
                486,
                431
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Keywords—resonant accelerometer; silicon on glass (SOG); temperature sensitivity; thermal stress; bias stability "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                68,
                441,
                486,
                470
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "I. INTRODUCTION "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                214,
                486,
                354,
                500
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Micromachined accelerometers have shown potential for high-precision applications such as strategic-grade navigation [1,2], seismology [3,4] and gravimetry [5,6] in recent years. High-performance micromachined resonant accelerometers (MRAs), based on the force-frequency characteristics of high-Q resonators, have become very attractive due to direct frequency output [1-3]. However, the temperature drifts of the bias and the scale factor limit the long-term stability of the MRA operation. There are two major sources of structure-dependent temperature drift [7]. Firstly, the Young's modulus of silicon used as sensing structure material varies with temperature change, which will result in the natural frequency change of the resonator [8]. Secondly, the mismatch of the coefficients of thermal expansion (CTEs) between the silicon structure and the glass substrate will generate thermal stress. The first drift error can be greatly decreased by a differential design of two symmetric resonators but the second one will worsen the differential effect. In addition, the die attach process during the device vacuum packaging will generate unpredictable thermal stress [2,9]. This paper proposes an improved structure design and a special-shaped isolation substrate to reduce the thermal stress effect on bias stability of the MRA. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                71,
                505,
                488,
                821
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "II. METHODS "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                228,
                840,
                336,
                854
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "A double-ended tuning fork (DETF) resonator with a pair of micro-levers is shown in Fig. 1. The MRA device was fabricated based on silicon on glass (SOG) process [1]. Since "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                66,
                859,
                486,
                902
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "the CTE of the BF33 glass substrate  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "(\\alpha_{\\mathrm{g}})"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " is slightly larger than that of the silicon structure  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "(\\alpha_{\\mathrm{s}})"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", the  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "x"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "-axis distance between the anchors  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "(\\delta)"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " will increase as the temperature rises  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "(\\Delta T)"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " [10]. In this case, the natural frequency  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "(f_0)"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " of the resonator will increase due to the larger tensile force generated in the DETF, as modeled in (1). "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                506,
                271,
                926,
                354
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "equation_interline",
            "content": {
                "math_content": "\\Delta f _ {0} = k \\left(\\alpha_ {\\mathrm {g}} - \\alpha_ {\\mathrm {s}}\\right) \\Delta T \\tag {1}",
                "math_type": "latex",
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/5d1bc2152c17035a809fae5120f79faba9bcad5db01dc8a806e5e46f721ec91f.jpg"
                }
            },
            "bbox": [
                651,
                371,
                926,
                388
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "In principle, the thermal stress coefficient  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "(k)"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " is dominated by  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\delta"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". If  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "\\delta = 0"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", which can be implemented by using an inverted beam design, the thermal stress along the acceleration-sensitive axis can be decreased greatly. The layout of the suspension beams also influences the thermal stress. The four anchors of the suspension beams should be arranged symmetrically, relative to the expansion center, and be close to each other. An improved structure design is illustrated schematically in Fig. 2. Finite element simulation shows that the theoretical temperature drift caused by the thermal expansion of silicon and glass is only  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "-0.016\\mathrm{Hz} / {}^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", as shown in Fig. 3. The total temperature drift coefficient (TDC) of a single resonator is  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "-0.576\\mathrm{Hz} / {}^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ", which is mainly owing to the Young's modulus drift. This design aims to minimize the effect of thermal expansion and improve the TDC consistency of two DETF resonators. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                506,
                396,
                928,
                618
            ]
        },
