                691
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The bias stability is one of the most crucial performance parameters for high-precision accelerometers. Fig. 8 shows the output acceleration of one MRA device (M1). The device is mounted at  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0\\mathrm{g}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " position and the test environment is under room temperature. The frequency output is acquired at a sampling rate of  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "1\\mathrm{Hz}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " for a duration of 12 hours, where no temperature compensation or data smoothing is used in the plotted curves. It is clear that the MRA reached thermal equilibrium within two hours. The standard deviation of the later 10-hour data is  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "2.7~\\mu \\mathrm{g}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " and the bias change of the last 1-hour output is only  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.7~\\mu \\mathrm{g}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                66,
                696,
                486,
                849
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/0c7751401486d5fa02f9cac459a470d60a0d5867527b492aed9e822e5081a696.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig. 7. The measured temperature drift of one typical device (M1). "
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
                570,
                77,
                864,
                304
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "image",
            "content": {
                "image_source": {
                    "path": "images/90d7123ad1a806e33d0b582dc99e0016d10d20d93b7e7ff7acb10a5fd09b8df0.jpg"
                },
                "image_caption": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "Fig. 8. Measured bias stability under room temperature. "
                    }
                ],
                "image_footnote": []
            },
            "bbox": [
                550,
                345,
                864,
                592
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "The measured results indicate that the MRA devices presented in this work exhibit good temperature-insensitive characteristics and high long-term stability. Along with the low noise design [12], the MRA has shown potential performance for high-precision strategic-grade navigation and gravity measurement applications. "
                    }
                ]
            },
            "bbox": [
                508,
                622,
                926,
                708
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "title",
            "content": {
                "title_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "IV. CONCLUSION "
                    }
                ],
                "level": 1
            },
            "bbox": [
                655,
                720,
                787,
                734
            ]
        },
        {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": {
                "paragraph_content": [
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": "This paper presents a novel MRA structure design with optimized anchor locations and additional H-shaped isolation glass substrate to reduce the thermal stress effect. Experimental results show that the MRA temperature drift generated in both the microfabrication and device packaging is reduced greatly. The differential temperature drift coefficient is reduced to  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "10.5\\mu \\mathrm{g} / ^{\\circ}\\mathrm{C}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": ". The measured bias stability is  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "0.7~\\mu \\mathrm{g}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " in one hour and  "
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "equation_inline",
                        "content": "2.7~\\mu \\mathrm{g}"
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "text",
                        "content": " in 10 hours under room temperature. Future work will focus on the temperature drift compensation and constant temperature control techniques to further improve the long-term stability. "
                    }
